    "text": "Erdős Problem #790: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. Let $l(n)$ be maximal such that if $A\\subset\\mathbb{Z}$ with $\\lvert A\\rvert=n$ then there exists a sum-free $B\\subseteq A$ with $\\lvert B\\rvert \\geq l(n)$ - that is, $B$ is such that there are no solutions to\\[a_1=a_2+\\cdots+a_r\\]with $a_i\\in B$ all distinct.\n\nEstimate $l(n)$. In particular, is it true that $l(n)n^{-1/2}\\to \\infty$? Is it true that $l(n)< n^{1-c}$ for some $c>0$? Prize: no. Tags: additive combinatorics.",
